hat nobody was coming to save me. I started learning out of necessity—how systems work, how habits work, how mindset works—because staying the same wasn’t an option anymore.2. The pain that pushed me:Feeling stuck while knowing I had people depending on me. That mix of frustration, fear, and responsibility is a powerful teacher. I didn’t want to just survive—I wanted to become someone my kids could look up to.3. Coaching / consulting path:Not a formal coach yet. I’m more in the “learn it, apply it, share it” phase. I help people by breaking things down simply, sharing what I’ve tested in real life, and being honest about what works and what doesn’t.4. How long I’ve been in self-improvement:Several years of trial, error, setbacks, and course corrections. Still learning every day.5. Current stage of my journey:Actively building. Still sharpening habits, tightening discipline, and leveling up consistency. Not finished—just committed.Looking forward to learning from everyone here and contributing where I can. 👊"},{"role":"assistant","content":"@Devon Hoyt epic, Devon! Thank you for sharing. Only when the pain of staying the same outweights the pain of facing the resistance and making a change is when we'll finally make a change. I heard from great men that the moment in which the truly became men was the very moment in which they realized nobody was coming to save them and they had to figure things out by themselves, it has been my experience as well.I'm really glad to have you here and looking forward to connect."}]}
