ke the others my age. Luckily this is when YouTube began to take off and people starting sharing a lot of value around fitness and nutrition. Trial and error got me to losing 20kg's eventually, and I've been able to keep most of it off ever since. When I saw putting some work in could give me results, I realized the same thing could be done in other aspects.The following years I became a lot more extroverted, social and confident. Through studying social work and psychology I got into coaching people to build a better life. I was good doing those jobs, and now I've taken it online and moved to Thailand. Felt like a good next step in my self-improvement. Have been coaching people now for 7 years already. Learned a whole lot. About people, training techniques, but probably even more about myself.I just think the self-improvement journey is amazing, and I wish everyone can experience seeing themselves improve into a better version and better life, step by step. Does it ever end? I don't think so. There's always room for improvement. It can feel tiring at times, but I wouldn't want to have it any other way.Can't wait to connect more with all of you guys.- Miguel"},{"role":"assistant","content":"@Thomas El Nadir brother, quite an epic story. What a journey! So many of us start motivated by one of the most basic desires we men have and that leads us to discover ourselves and start improving, some start with the gym, some start with game and social skills but in the end we all arrive at the same holistic understanding if we stay consistent on our paths for long enough.Really glad to have you here with us, brother. This is truly were you belong. And now it's time to build something truly wonderful with all the wisdom we have accumulated and give back to the world that has been so abundantly generous to us."}]}
